<DOC><DOCNO> AP880527-0301 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 0908EDT</FILEID><FIRST>d f PM-Stern'sClosing     05-27 0174</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Stern's Closing,0182</SECOND><HEAD>Stern's To Close Seven Stores In Philly Area, Newspaper Says</HEAD><DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   After a two-year effort to crack thePhiladelphia market, Stern's is preparing to throw in the towel andsell its seven department stores in the city and suburbs, apublished report said today.   Retailing sources quoted in the Philadelphia Inquirer saidStern's parent, Toronto-based Campeau Corp., has found a buyer forthe stores and should announce a sale within several weeks. Thebuyer was not identified.   Stern's, a 27-store chain based in Paramus, N.J., moved into thePhiladelphia market in July 1986 by taking over the Gimbels storesin the area.   But Stern's has not been able to improve the performance of theseven former Gimbels, which had sales of $134.2 million in 1985,according to unidentified trade sources quoted by the newspaper.   The buyer is expected to be a retailer that caters to a lower-ormoderate-income clientele, possibly a discount chain, the Inquirerreported.   Joele Frank, a spokeswoman for Campeau, had no comment on thereport.</TEXT></DOC>